'generate_query[1].predict' predictor demos: [Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['Nikolay Mitrofanovich Krylov | Nikolay Mitrofanovich Krylov (Russian: Никола́й Митрофа́нович Крыло́в , Ukrainian: Микола Митрофанович Крилов ) (29 November [O.S. 17 November] 1879 – May 11, 1955) was a Russian and Soviet mathematician known for works on interpolation, non-linear mechanics, and numerical methods for solving equations of mathematical physics.', 'Alexander Ivanovich Mikhailov | Alexander Ivanovich Mikhailov, or A. I. Mikhailov ( December 6, 1905, Russian Empire – February 6, 1988, Moscow) was a Russian/Soviet Engineer and Information Scientist. He was one of the most influential thinkers related to the field of Information Science in the Soviet Union and the Eastern bloc.', 'Mikhail Khovanov | Mikhail Khovanov (Russian: Михаил Хованов ; born 1972) is a Russian-American professor of mathematics at Columbia University. He graduated from Moscow State School 57 mathematical class in 1988. He earned a PhD in mathematics from Yale University in 1997, where he studied under Igor Frenkel. His interests include knot theory and algebraic topology. He is known for the Khovanov homology for links, introduced in his paper "A categorification of the Jones polynomial", which he published while at UC Davis. This was one of the first examples of categorification and is quoted in knot theory.'], 'question': 'Are Alexander Ivanovich Mikhailov and Nikolay Mitrofanovich Krylov both Russian?', 'reasoning': 'To determine if Alexander Ivanovich Mikhailov and Nikolay Mitrofanovich Krylov are both Russian, I need to examine the information provided in the context. The context mentions that Nikolay Mitrofanovich Krylov was a Russian and Soviet mathematician. Similarly, it states that Alexander Ivanovich Mikhailov was a Russian/Soviet Engineer and Information Scientist. Therefore, both individuals are Russian.', 'search_query': 'Are Nikolay Mitrofanovich Krylov and Alexander Ivanovich Mikhailov both Russian?'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['Moisés Solana | Moisés Solana Arciniega (December 26, 1935 – July 27, 1969) was a racing driver from Mexico. He participated in eight Formula One World Championship Grands Prix, debuting on October 27, 1963, and scoring no championship points. He also participated in one non-Championship Formula One race. He also took part in Formula Two in 1968 with Team Lotus at the Jarama Circuit near Madrid, Spain. His first racing events were in a 1954 special (the "Solana Sports"), built by Javiér Solana. Solana was also a proficient Jai alai player and his racing career was partly funded by this.', "Solana (automobile) | Solana is a cottage manufacturer of sports, racing, and kids' automobiles. The family run company has operated since 1936, with a total production of fewer than fifty cars; the majority of them one-offs. The family is heavily involved in motor sports; the most prominent member was Moisés Solana, who raced family-built cars and later in Formula One.", 'Nolberto Solano | Nolberto Albino "Ñol" Solano Todco (born 12 December 1974), commonly known as Nobby Solano, is a retired Peruvian professional footballer, and former manager of Peruvian Primera División club Universitario de Deportes and Canadian semi-professional team Internacional de Toronto, from League1 Ontario. He spent much of his playing career in the English Premier League and also played 95 times for Peru between 1994 and 2009. He is a popular figure in his native Peru, where he is seen as one of the most famous Peruvians, appearing on telephone cards and having his wedding televised live.'], 'question': ' Moisés Solano helped fund his racing career by playing a sport that is a variation of what game? ', 'reasoning': 'The context mentions that Moisés Solana was a proficient Jai alai player and that his racing career was partly funded by this. Therefore, the sport that is a variation of the game that Moisés Solana played to fund his racing career is Jai alai.', 'search_query': 'What is the origin or variation of the sport Jai alai?'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['Rap Name | "Rap Name" is the debut single of American rapper Obie Trice, released as a limited edition vinyl recording, taken from the deluxe edition of the soundtrack to the film "8 Mile". The song features vocals from fellow-label mate Eminem, who sampled the track in two tracks for his album "The Eminem Show", released earlier in 2002. These tracks are "Drips" and the intro of the album\'s lead single, "Without Me", as well as a few other lines from the song. The song also features a vocal sample of The Notorious B.I.G. from his song "Long Kiss Goodnight" from the album "Life After Death". The official video was filmed in Detroit with featured cameo appearances by Eminem\'s group D12.', 'Don\'t Say Goodnight (It\'s Time for Love) | "Don\'t Say Goodnight (It\'s Time for Love)" is a 1980 quiet storm soul record by The Isley Brothers, released on their T-Neck imprint. The song, which was released as an answer of sorts to Teddy Pendergrass\' hit, "Turn Off the Lights", was an ode to love sung by Ronald Isley, who begs his lady in his trademark falsetto to give him her love, stating if "people say that love is for the giving/so lemme love you, girl". Released as the first single off their 1980 platinum album, "Go All the Way", the song was also their last Top 40 pop hit in 16 years, peaking at number 39 pop while reaching number one on the R&B singles chart. In 2006, the 7" single\'s instrumental B-side was sampled by J Dilla on the instrumental album "Donuts".', 'Goodnight Kiss | "Goodnight Kiss" is a song recorded by American country music artist Randy Houser. It was released in September 2013 as the third single from his third studio album, "How Country Feels". Houser wrote the song with Rob Hatch and Jason Sellers.'], 'question': 'In which year was the album released which included the single "Long Kiss Goodnight", which was used as a sample in the song "Rap name"?', 'reasoning': 'The song "Long Kiss Goodnight" is mentioned in the context, and it is a sample used in the song "Rap Name". The context also mentions that "Long Kiss Goodnight" is from The Notorious B.I.G.\'s album "Life After Death". Therefore, the year of the album\'s release is needed.', 'search_query': 'What year was the album "Life After Death" by The Notorious B.I.G. released?'}) (input_keys=None)]

'generate_answer.predict' predictor demos: [Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['Nikolay Mitrofanovich Krylov | Nikolay Mitrofanovich Krylov (Russian: Никола́й Митрофа́нович Крыло́в , Ukrainian: Микола Митрофанович Крилов ) (29 November [O.S. 17 November] 1879 – May 11, 1955) was a Russian and Soviet mathematician known for works on interpolation, non-linear mechanics, and numerical methods for solving equations of mathematical physics.', 'Alexander Ivanovich Mikhailov | Alexander Ivanovich Mikhailov, or A. I. Mikhailov ( December 6, 1905, Russian Empire – February 6, 1988, Moscow) was a Russian/Soviet Engineer and Information Scientist. He was one of the most influential thinkers related to the field of Information Science in the Soviet Union and the Eastern bloc.', 'Mikhail Khovanov | Mikhail Khovanov (Russian: Михаил Хованов ; born 1972) is a Russian-American professor of mathematics at Columbia University. He graduated from Moscow State School 57 mathematical class in 1988. He earned a PhD in mathematics from Yale University in 1997, where he studied under Igor Frenkel. His interests include knot theory and algebraic topology. He is known for the Khovanov homology for links, introduced in his paper "A categorification of the Jones polynomial", which he published while at UC Davis. This was one of the first examples of categorification and is quoted in knot theory.', 'Mikhail Mitrofanov | Mikhail Mitrofanov is a Russian rugby league player who represented his country in the 2000 World Cup. He kicked three goals during the tournament.', 'Nikolay Mikhailovich Volkov | Nikolay Mikhailovich Volkov (Russian: Николай Михайлович Волков ) (born December 19, 1951) is a Russian politician.'], 'question': 'Are Alexander Ivanovich Mikhailov and Nikolay Mitrofanovich Krylov both Russian?', 'reasoning': 'Alexander Ivanovich Mikhailov was a Russian/Soviet Engineer and Information Scientist, and Nikolay Mitrofanovich Krylov was a Russian and Soviet mathematician. Both of them are described as Russian or Soviet in the provided context.', 'answer': 'Yes'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['Moisés Solana | Moisés Solana Arciniega (December 26, 1935 – July 27, 1969) was a racing driver from Mexico. He participated in eight Formula One World Championship Grands Prix, debuting on October 27, 1963, and scoring no championship points. He also participated in one non-Championship Formula One race. He also took part in Formula Two in 1968 with Team Lotus at the Jarama Circuit near Madrid, Spain. His first racing events were in a 1954 special (the "Solana Sports"), built by Javiér Solana. Solana was also a proficient Jai alai player and his racing career was partly funded by this.', "Solana (automobile) | Solana is a cottage manufacturer of sports, racing, and kids' automobiles. The family run company has operated since 1936, with a total production of fewer than fifty cars; the majority of them one-offs. The family is heavily involved in motor sports; the most prominent member was Moisés Solana, who raced family-built cars and later in Formula One.", 'Nolberto Solano | Nolberto Albino "Ñol" Solano Todco (born 12 December 1974), commonly known as Nobby Solano, is a retired Peruvian professional footballer, and former manager of Peruvian Primera División club Universitario de Deportes and Canadian semi-professional team Internacional de Toronto, from League1 Ontario. He spent much of his playing career in the English Premier League and also played 95 times for Peru between 1994 and 2009. He is a popular figure in his native Peru, where he is seen as one of the most famous Peruvians, appearing on telephone cards and having his wedding televised live.', 'Jai alai | Jai alai ( ; Basque: ] ) is a sport involving a ball bounced off a walled space by accelerating it to high speeds with a hand-held device (cesta). It is a variation of Basque pelota. The term, coined by Serafin Baroja in 1875, is also often loosely applied to the fronton (the open-walled playing area) where the sport is played. The game is called "zesta-punta" (basket tip) in Basque.', 'Whirlyball | Whirlyball is a team sport invented by Stan Mangum that combines elements of basketball and jai alai, or rather a combination of lacrosse and bumper cars , with the players riding Whirlybugs, small electric vehicles similar to bumper cars. Because play requires a special court, it is played in only a handful of locations in the United States and Canada.', 'NJAA | The National Jai-Alai Association (NJAA) is a non-profit organization devoted to promoting and preserving the sport of jai-alai.'], 'question': ' Moisés Solano helped fund his racing career by playing a sport that is a variation of what game? ', 'reasoning': 'The context mentions that Moisés Solana was a proficient Jai alai player and that his racing career was partly funded by this. Jai alai is described in the context as "a sport involving a ball bounced off a walled space by accelerating it to high speeds with a hand-held device (cesta). It is a variation of Basque pelota."', 'answer': 'Basque pelota'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['Rap Name | "Rap Name" is the debut single of American rapper Obie Trice, released as a limited edition vinyl recording, taken from the deluxe edition of the soundtrack to the film "8 Mile". The song features vocals from fellow-label mate Eminem, who sampled the track in two tracks for his album "The Eminem Show", released earlier in 2002. These tracks are "Drips" and the intro of the album\'s lead single, "Without Me", as well as a few other lines from the song. The song also features a vocal sample of The Notorious B.I.G. from his song "Long Kiss Goodnight" from the album "Life After Death". The official video was filmed in Detroit with featured cameo appearances by Eminem\'s group D12.', 'Don\'t Say Goodnight (It\'s Time for Love) | "Don\'t Say Goodnight (It\'s Time for Love)" is a 1980 quiet storm soul record by The Isley Brothers, released on their T-Neck imprint. The song, which was released as an answer of sorts to Teddy Pendergrass\' hit, "Turn Off the Lights", was an ode to love sung by Ronald Isley, who begs his lady in his trademark falsetto to give him her love, stating if "people say that love is for the giving/so lemme love you, girl". Released as the first single off their 1980 platinum album, "Go All the Way", the song was also their last Top 40 pop hit in 16 years, peaking at number 39 pop while reaching number one on the R&B singles chart. In 2006, the 7" single\'s instrumental B-side was sampled by J Dilla on the instrumental album "Donuts".', 'Goodnight Kiss | "Goodnight Kiss" is a song recorded by American country music artist Randy Houser. It was released in September 2013 as the third single from his third studio album, "How Country Feels". Houser wrote the song with Rob Hatch and Jason Sellers.', 'Life After Death | Life After Death is the second and final studio album by American rapper The Notorious B.I.G., released on March 25, 1997, on Bad Boy Records and Arista Records. A double album, it was released posthumously following his death on March 9, 1997. It features collaborations with guest artists such as 112, Jay-Z, Lil\' Kim, Mase, Bone Thugs-n-Harmony, Too $hort, Angela Winbush, D.M.C. of Run-D.M.C. , R. Kelly, The LOX and Puff Daddy. "Life After Death" exhibits The Notorious B.I.G. further delving into the mafioso rap subgenre. The album is a sequel to his first album, "Ready to Die", and picks up where the last song, "Suicidal Thoughts", ends.', 'Ready to Die | Ready to Die is the debut studio album by American rapper The Notorious B.I.G.; it was released on September 13, 1994, by Bad Boy Records and Arista Records. The label\'s first release, the album features production by Bad Boy founder Sean "Puffy" Combs, Easy Mo Bee, Chucky Thompson, DJ Premier and Lord Finesse, among others. Recording for the album took place during 1993-94 at The Hit Factory and D&D Studios in New York City. The partly autobiographical album tells the story of B.I.G.\'s experiences as a young criminal. "Ready to Die" was the only studio album released during his life, as he was murdered sixteen days prior to the release of his second album, "Life After Death" in 1997.', 'Hypnotize (The Notorious B.I.G. song) | "Hypnotize" is a single by American rapper The Notorious B.I.G., released as the first single from his album "Life After Death" on March 1, 1997 and the last song released in his lifetime, as he was killed in a drive-by shooting a week later. It was the fifth song by a credited artist to hit number one posthumously. It was ranked at number 30 on "Rolling Stone"\' s 50 greatest rap songs of all time in hip hop history.'], 'question': 'In which year was the album released which included the single "Long Kiss Goodnight", which was used as a sample in the song "Rap name"?', 'reasoning': 'The song "Long Kiss Goodnight" is from the album "Life After Death" by The Notorious B.I.G., which was released on March 25, 1997. The song "Rap Name" by Obie Trice features a vocal sample from "Long Kiss Goodnight".', 'answer': '1997'}) (input_keys=None)]

